<p><strong>Search engine optimization</strong>Â (<strong>SEO</strong>) is the process of improving the quality and quantity ofÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_traffic">website traffic</a>Â to aÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Website">website</a>Â or aÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_page">web page</a>Â fromÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Web_search_engine">search engines</a>.SEO targets unpaid traffic (known as "natural" or "<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organic_search">organic</a>" results) rather than direct traffic orÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Online_advertising">paid traffic</a>. Unpaid traffic may originate from different kinds of searches, includingÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_search">image search</a>,Â <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_search">video search</a>,Â <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Academic_databases_and_search_engines">academic search</a>,Â news search, and industry-specificÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertical_search">vertical search</a>Â engines.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>As anÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internet_marketing">Internet marketing</a>Â strategy, SEO considers how search engines work, the computer-programmedÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm">algorithms</a>Â that dictate search engine behavior, what people search for, the actual search terms orÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keyword_research">keywords</a>Â typed into search engines, and which search engines are preferred by their targeted audience. SEO is performed because a website will receive more visitors from a search engine when websites rank higher on theÂ <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Search_engine_results_page">search engine results page</a>Â (SERP). These visitors can then potentially be converted into customers.</p>
